The act was mainly put into play by Obama because the countries in question could not provide adequate documentation regarding the effects of trophy hunting. Trophy hunting in other countries is still legal and can actually improve population growth as Ana briefly mentioned. Killing off older elephants that are no longer capable of reproduction can provide more opportunities for effective mating. Also, the conservation funding angle can, if used properly, be quite effective in improving population growth. Now that the regulation has been reversed, it is a gamble whether or not the intricacies of the trophy hunting process will be done in such a way as to help local economies and elephant sustainability in the two respective countries.

column13: Also, trophy hunting by wealthy foreigners is quite different from the hunting of ivory by opportunistic poachers. The former is more controllable and, therefore, can lead to more helpful results. The latter is brutal and secretive which leads to decreased populations and less effective habitats.

First off, I am A-Okay with hunting in the "eat what you kill" variety. I do NOT like the concept of trophy hunting. I've always thought that it undermines the integrity of what hunters do. That's why I don't bat an eye at an African tribe brutally killing an elephant or hippo by spearing it over and over again because I know they'll use it to sustain themselves, whereas I don't much care for trophy hunters, unless they're spear hunting or doing something that gives the animal equal chance. Blowing away an elephant with a .700 nitro express from 100 yards away is hardly a "hunt".

All this said, I'm failing to see where they're making the relationship between government sponsored and approved trophy hunting and the black market ivory trade, which is where your poachers come in. The elephant is GOING to be hunted by these trophy hunters, whether or not you and I like it. With that fact being as it may, I don't see the problem with making these hunters jump through hoops and pay boatloads of money to bring back their trophy when the money goes toward conservation. For those not in the know, businesses such as Ducks Unlimited have contributed more money that PETA towards wildlife conservation. Several times over, in fact. To conflate poaching with documented trophy hunting for conservation's benefit is extremely disingenuous, but I'm not too surprised considered that TYT spins and lampoons anything connected to Donald Trump.

column5:
Aldo Leopold; A Monument to the last Passenger Pigeon (Wisconsin: 1947) 
"It is a century now since Darwin gave us the first glimpse of the origin of species. We know now what was unknown to all the preceding caravan of ­generations: that man is only a fellow-voyager with other creatures in the Odyssey of evolution, and that his captaincy of the adventuring ship conveys the power, but not necessarily the right, to discard at will among the crew. We should, in the century since Darwin, have achieved a sense of community with living things, and of wonder over the magnitude and duration of the ­biotic enterprise.

For one species to mourn the death of another is a new thing under the sun. The Cro-Magnon who slew the last mammoth thought only of steaks. The sportsman who shot the last pigeon thought only of his prowess. The sailor who clubbed the last auk thought of nothing at all. But we, who have lost our pigeons, mourn the loss. Had the funeral been ours, the pigeons would hardly have mourned us. In this fact, rather than in Mr. Vandevar Bush’s bombs, or Mr. DuPont’s nylons, lies objective evidence of our superiority over the beasts."

The bolded words in this excerpt describe trophy hunters, which are the antitheses to conservation.

First I want to say that it's no surprise that this is something happening under the Trump administration. He's running the country for whatever suits him and his family. Period.

Though, put simply, it is up to those countries to protect those endangered species. There isn't much we can do other than try to show leadership and set an example. And honestly I think the United States has set a fantastic example on how to treat wildlife over the past 100 years or so. (Not when it comes to factory farming, but when it comes to stuff like the Game and Fish boards. If you don't believe me, pick a crime; commit it in front an officer and see what happens. Then, do the same crime in a national forest in front of a wildlife officer and see what happens. :D You'll get a ticket for littering in the city, and you'll get your house searched for littering in the Forest.) The money people pay to hunt these animals does great things for these animals, and not only that, killing almost every animal - if not EVERY SINGLE animal - these conservationists allow to be killed is necessary anyways. After the story about the Lion the dentist killed, a lot of conservation money was lost and a ton of problem lions were put down anyways. I think when someone hunts these animals, the majority of everything should go to the locals. But I don't see a problem with allowing whatever kind of trophy the conservation society there deems fit for a person to keep, allowing that person to keep and bring back. Hell, they could even charge extra money for something like that. 

Also, I want to be clear that I don't believe in hunting for sport at all. I know that a lot of the people that go do this... that's WHY they are there. But, if somebody is going to have to go out and kill a problem animal anyways, why not take a bunch of money from an asshat that has never hunted without paying for it to do it?

The last thing I'll say in support of hunting is this, if you eat meat - but you're against hunting; you're just as big of an asshole as you view trophy hunters. I don't have a problem with farming... I have a problem with factory farming. Unfortunately, that's where most of the meat you buy nowadays comes from. If you can't bring yourself to either hunt, shoot, and then at least gut the animal, or to slaughter an animal; maybe you shouldn't eat meat. When I kill a deer I gut it myself, but I bring it to a professional afterwards to butcher it, so as little meat is wasted as possible. I'll still eat meat bought from the grocery store, and sometimes I still go to taco bell; but after I killed and gutted my first deer, it happens a lot less often. I feel much better about eating it if I did it myself.

Once again, it's no surprise that this is something happening under the Trump administration.

There is one more point that they didn't cover here. The elephants are peaceful and very smart animals. They can remember events (especially traumatic ones) for a very long time.They are also very devoted to the members of their herd/family. When these fuckers hunt down elephants, the younger members of the herd are usually left out because their tusks are not developed enough to sell well or to make a decent trophy. When the young calf see its mother, father or sibling butchered by humans, they develop something similar to PTSD. They grow up very aggressive and dangerous towards other animals and especially humans. Eventually they attack (and possibly kill) someone and have to be put down themselves. It is a vicious circle which will ultimately lead to the extinction of the species in their natural habitat.

The title of the video is intentionally misleading. Elephants are endangered but can be legally shot for $100-200k. The animal is preselected and is typically very old, is no longer breeding, or has a lower question of life. The money spent to kill the animal goes nearly ENTIRELY back to the preserves and the people that work near and around them. 

Trumps action only allows hunters to bring back elephant trophies from these legal and paid hunts (I.e. tusks, bones, etc). It incentivizes more big game hunters now that they can bring trophies stateside. This literally helps preserves and animals. It HELPS.

I can’t even read all of these comments because the stupidity is too much to handle. Mankind does not balance out nature. Mankind disrupts nature. Nature is constantly tilting towards equilibrium through homeostasis, but in order to return to a sustainable ecosystem, some species often have to die off in order to for it to achieve balance again. This is especially true when there is a sudden, drastic change in the population of one species (like when they’re hunted to near-extinction) and the rest of the environment doesn’t have time to adapt & evolve. The imbalance causes chaos before it returns to sustainability. All life in every ecosystem is interconnected. You remove one species, and it will affect the rest in some way. So don’t try to oversimplify an extremely complex concept.

When one member of the herd dies, they experience the same emotions that we do and mourn their dead. When a member of that herd is murdered, it literally traumatizes them to such extents that there have been cases resembling psychosis & PTSD-like behavior, and even serial-killing elephants that actively seek out humans and kill them out of rage. They feel the same kind of pain that we feel when we lose someone we love. And their bonds are so much stronger than our own.

lach10211 -  I recommend learning the correct usage of your/you’re before attempting to grapple with animal conservation.   Sure, big game hunts cost $ but only a small percentage of the money trophy hunters pay is allocated toward conservation or local communities (approx 3%). Trophy hunting is also harmful to animal populations....killing a male lion leaves his fellow pride leaders open to challenges from other males. If a new male does come in, they could kill an entire generation of cubs, which means that the permit for one lion hunt leads to the death of several animals.   Finally, the biggest rebuttal to the hunting-helps-populations argument is in the numbers. Lions have lost 95 percent of their population since the 1940s. The African elephant population has dropped from several million at the turn of the century to roughly 500,000 today. During the past century hunting has been the primary - if not only - method of conservation, but the perilously low numbers of these animals proves that hunting is ineffective as a conservation method.
